      "role": "user",
      "content": "okay that makes more sense. so if the lawyer or title company is the one holding the money, do they just keep it in a standard savings account or is there something special about how those funds are protected during the process? like what prevents the money from just disappearing if something goes wrong?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Great question! The funds held in an escrow account are not kept in a standard savings account. Instead, they are held in a special type of account that is designed to ensure the security and proper handling of the money during the real estate transaction process.\n\nThese accounts are typically insured by the Financial Services Commission of Ontario (FSCO) up to a certain amount, which provides an additional layer of protection for the funds. The escrow agent, such as a lawyer or title company, is bound by professional and legal obligations to manage the funds responsibly and in accordance with the terms of the escrow agreement.\n\nIf something goes wrong, there are legal remedies available to you as the buyer. For example, if the seller fails to meet their obligations, you may have the right to withhold the funds or take legal action to recover them. Conversely, if you fail to meet your obligations, the seller may have the right to retain the funds or seek compensation.\n\nThe escrow process is designed to protect both parties involved in the transaction and to ensure that the funds are only released when all the necessary conditions are met. It's a way to provide peace of mind and to help ensure that the transaction goes smoothly. I hope this answers your question about how the funds are protected during the",
